Class CrossPanel

  • All Implemented Interfaces:

    public class CrossPanel
extends javax.swing.JPanel
    The panel containing the visual representation of the crossword puzzle and contains all the methods needed in order to highlight clues and enable the user to type correctly flowing across the textfields.
    Author:
    Daniel

      • solve

        public void solve()
        This was just used for testing but can be activated by entering "SOLVEALL" as the username. It will solve all the clues and input the answers into the correct places on the display.

      • highlight

        public void highlight(CrossPanel.GridPanel clicked,
             int clueDirection,
             int typing)
        Highlights the selected panel in the grid one colour, and will highlight all the other panels in that clue another colour. Will toggle the highlighted clue for those panels which are in both an across and a down clue. Will highlight the panel with the keyboard focus as the selected panel when typing in an answer.
        Parameters:
        clicked - The selected panel to be highlighted.
        clueDirection - The direction of the clue clicked on in the sidepanel. 1 means across and 2 means down.
        typing - Whether the user is typing or not, 0 means not, 1 means typing.

      • fillCorrect

        public void fillCorrect()
        Fills in all the answers for the clues which have been marked as solved. Used when loading a crossword from a file.

      • checkCorrect

        public void checkCorrect(int clue,
                int direction,
                java.lang.String answer)
        Checks a given answer against a given clue and it's direction. If the answer is correct the clue is marked as solved and the user and time and date it was solved are saved, if not then it is marked as unsolved.
        Parameters:
        clue - The clue number to check against.
        direction - The direction the clue is in, 0 means across and 1 means down.
        answer - The given answer to check against the clue.
